We can use a `while`(#e7e8ea) loop to traverse a 1D array.
- We use a variable called `index`(#e7e8ea) to keep track of our current position. It is initialized to 0 to start at the first element.
- The condition for the `while`(#e7e8ea) loop checks if the current value assigned to `index`(#e7e8ea) is less than the length of the 1D array. It will repeat as long as the condition is `true`(#e7e8ea).
- We can then use the current value assigned to `index`(#e7e8ea) to access the element at that position in the 1D array.
- To move to the next element, we add 1 to the `index`(#e7e8ea) variable.

```
int[] scores = {75, 90, 83};

int index = 0;

while (index < scores.length) {
  System.out.println(scores[index]);
  index += 1;
}
```
